projectInfo.name: Camp mapping HCR- Mentao - Djibo, Burkina Faso
projectInfo.shortDescription:
The increase of violence in Mali led thousands of people to flee across the border into Burkina Faso’s North Region.
More than 25,000 refugees have  found refuge in Burkina Faso since the start of the Mali conflict in 2012.
With the rise of extremist and inter-communal violence in Mali, UNHCR now fears more displacement and increase humanitarian needs.
As part of these efforts, CartONG is supporting UNHCR on running a survey on Water,  Sanitation and Hygiene  (WASH) practises in the camp. Mapping the camp will help organize the survey and will be useful in planning camp management in the long run.
projectInfo.description:
* Author : Missing Maps / CartONG
* Requesting organization : HCR
* Priority : Medium

[![Video](http://img.youtube.com/vi/JFNoEOizdXs/0.jpg)](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JFNoEOizdXs)

The increase of violence in Mali led thousands of people to flee across the border into Burkina Faso’s North Region.

The UNHCR, the UN Refugee Agency, estimates that between February and April 2018 more than 3,000 Malians fled their country. These newcomers added up to the 24,000 refugees who have already found shelter in Burkina Faso since the start of the Mali conflict in 2012.

They are mainly settled in two camps: Mentao near Djibo, and Goudoubo near Dori.
With the rise of extremist and inter-communal violence in Mali, UNHCR now fears more displacement and increased humanitarian needs.

As the situation does not guarantee a close return to the many refugees, UNHCR is undertaking a number of actions to enable them to settle in Burkina Faso in a more sustainable manner and under better conditions.

As part of these efforts, CartONG is supporting UNHCR on running a survey on Water,  Sanitation and Hygiene  (WASH) practises in the camp. Mapping the camp will help organize the survey and will be useful in planning camp management in the long run.
projectInfo.instructions:
Please divide you task if yours is too dense!

#Imagery details
You will use **Bing Aerial Imagery** imagery for this area.  

#Shelters

* **In the ID editor**: label the area as “Building”, then correct for right angles with the “S” key

* **In JOSM**: from the Tags/Memberships window, click “Add” and use the tag “building=yes”; then correct for right angles using the “Q” key

#Road network
Roads should be identified with respect to their economic and social role, not in terms of their visibility/viability. The best way to approach this is to use the existing road network and its connections to towns and villages.

* **In the ID editor**: please use *highway=residential*  (with the exception of major roads) 
* **In JOSM**: from the Tags/Memberships window, click “Add” and use the tag “highway=residential”

You soudn't have to use :

* *highway=primary*, *highway=secondary* or *highway=tertiary* : these are the main roads that connect towns. You shouldn’t need to create them for this project.

* *highway=track* (roads or paths which connect *fields only*) and “highway=path”(roads too narrow for a 4-wheel drive vehicle to pass)

The most important thing is to maintain consistency in the network. Every road should connect to another of greater importance and not to isolated roads.

See the Wiki page [Highway Africa Tag](http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Highway_Tag_Africa) for more information on the cartography of route networks in Africa. For a concrete example, see the [ cartographic guide for route networks in S. Kivu](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1X1BcmhLmsvT3uzAfe6jzctQy0VfpWPn_jT_gbb6HmK0/edit#slide=id.gd835ac67f_2_37)
